# taste-net — documentation overview

This is a small neural network, built entirely from raw numpy (no
PyTorch, no scikit-learn), trained to predict whether I would save
an image, using only my own labeled Pinterest data.

I built this to actually understand what's happening inside tools
like sentence-transformers, which I used in an earlier project
(chaos-organizer) without knowing the math underneath. Every file
here documents that understanding, built from scratch, in my own
words — worked through with an AI tutor across multiple sessions,
re-explained slowly wherever I got confused.

## How to read this

Go through the files in order — each one builds on the last:

1. **01_the_data.md** — how an image becomes 29 numbers
2. **02_neurons_and_layers.md** — the basic vocabulary
3. **03_the_weighted_sum.md** — how one neuron computes a score
4. **04_nonlinearity.md** — why one weighted sum alone isn't enough
5. **05_sigmoid.md** — turning a raw score into a probability
6. **06_loss_function.md** — measuring how wrong a prediction was
7. **07_backward_pass.md** — how the model corrects itself
8. **08_matrix_multiplication.md** — how this scales to real data
9. **glossary.md** — quick symbol lookup, once terms are familiar